<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <% if (htmlWebpackPlugin.options.isDevelopment) { %>
    <!--
      Development only. webpack-dev-server needs a websocket back to localhost
      for hot reload, and React Refresh evaluates the modules it injects. The
      packaged policy below is the one that ships; keep the two in step.
    -->
    <meta
      http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy"
      content="default-src 'none'; script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' 'unsafe-eval'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; img-src 'self' data:; font-src 'self' data:; connect-src 'self' ws://localhost:* http://localhost:*; base-uri 'none'; form-action 'none'; frame-ancestors 'none'; object-src 'none'"
    />
    <% } else { %>
    <!--
      Revealed secrets live in this renderer. `default-src 'none'` with
      `connect-src 'none'` means a compromised renderer — a malicious
      dependency, or script smuggled in through a record field — has nowhere to
      send them: no fetch, no XHR, no WebSocket, no beacon, no image ping.

      Nothing here needs the network. Every asset is bundled (see the extension
      CSP rule in AGENTS.md), and the daemon is reached through the
      contextBridge over a Unix socket, which CSP does not govern. Do not add a
      host to connect-src: doing so hands an attacker the egress this is here
      to deny.
    -->
    <meta
      http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy"
      content="default-src 'none'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; img-src 'self' data:; font-src 'self' data:; connect-src 'none'; base-uri 'none'; form-action 'none'; frame-ancestors 'none'; object-src 'none'"
    />
    <% } %>
    <title>Albear</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="root"></div>
  </body>
</html>
